            <p>Caroli's Disease (CD) is a rare congenital disorder
characterized by cystic dilatation of the intrahepatic
bile ducts. This report describes a patient with cholangiocarcinoma
arising in the setting of monolobar
CD. In spite of detailed investigations including
biliary enteric bypass and endoscopic retrograde
cholangiography, the diagnosis of mucinous cholangiocarcinoma
(CCA) was not made for almost one
year. The presentation, diagnosis and treatment of
monolobar CD and the association between monolobar
CD and biliary tract cancer are discussed.
Hepatic resection is the treatment of choice for
monolobar CD.</p>
